text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas]]%0a%0a!The Indiana Miami Tribe%0a%0a:Author: NickG%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA discussion of the Miami Tribe, specifically the Indiana Miami%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI chose the Miami [maɪˈæmɪ] Nation of Indians because I’m from Indiana. Originally, this tribe and the Miami Indians of Oklahoma were one tribe, but the U.S. removed most of the Miami from Indiana; an 1854 treaty with the U.S. government allowed the Indiana Miami to stay. They are also known as the “Myaamia,” but most of the websites have them identifying with the name “Miami.” However, they still call the language Myaamia. There are a number of treaties that have dealt with the Miami lands. Although the 1854 treaty allowed the Miami to be recognized by the government, in 1899, the Indiana Miami landed was illegally possessed by the government. Although they have tried to regain their land through things like petitioning the government in 1934 during the Indian Reorganization Act, these petitions have been denied. In 1989, they attempted again to regain control of their land, but were turned away.%0a%0aThe Miami tribe still preserves their language by using it in the administration, as well as hosting an annual week-long camp teaching the language to the Miami of Indiana children. There are 6000 individuals who are part of the Indiana Miami tribe throughout Indiana, and have a governing body consisting of chiefs from each of the five families who remained in Indiana when the Miami were removed. These families hold native speakers of the language, and there is a [[https://www.myaamiadictionary.org/dictionary2015/index.php | Myammia Dictionary]] that helps preserve the language.%0a%0aThe websites from non-Indigenous sources focus more on the history of the tribe (like their location over time, treaties regarding their land, where their language is spoken) and less on the cultural aspect of the tribe. Additionally, because it focuses on history, these websites do not say much about how the tribe is functioning currently. These sites include very little about the ongoing administration of the tribe, or the events the tribe sponsors. So, even though many of the facts are similar, these sites simply do go as in-depth as the indigenous ones.%0a%0ahttps://www.miamioh.edu/myaamia-center/about/index.html%0ahttp://www.miamiindians.org/preserving-the-language%0ahttps://myefe.com/transcription-pronunciation/miami%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miami_people%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210424-190019-782190#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!More in depth on reclamation efforts %0a-> - ZoeC%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aSource: Leonard2011-ChallengingExtinction.pdf%0a%0aIn this expansion, I would like to discuss the reclamation of the Miami tribe’s language more in depth. The article “Challenging “Extinction” through Modern Miami Language Practices” by Dr. Wesley Y. Leonard tackles the expectation that Native American languages are only long-gone aspects of a frozen past and a dead culture. This idea perpetuates erasure of Indigenous languages, or the idea that they are only meant to be talked about in past tense, as if these cultures and languages are not currently thriving and being used in both domestic and diplomatic contexts. %0a%0aHe discusses the new efforts surrounding the Miami language not as a reclamation, but as a reclamation. Revitalization is usually thought of as trying to achieve mass fluency, but Leonard is more concerned with reclaiming the language for cultural purposes. He writes, “When  we  talk  about  language  and  cultural  revitalization,  we  are  in  essence  referring  to  the  revitalization  of  belief,  value  and  knowledge  systems.  It  is  through  our  language  and  culture  that  we  express  those  ways  of  knowing.” The main focus is “breathing new life into it”, and applying it to the Miami tribe’s roles in the modern world. At cultural reclamation camps for children like eewansaapita camp, they learn basic vocabulary, a number song in myaamia, and ball games where the points are recorded in myaamia. Songs, games, and other regular communication are some of the methods being used to reclaim the Miami language and apply it to modern contexts.%0a%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210424-190019-782190#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a#foxbegin 210412-221659-758980#%0a(:if1 equal {$:Author} {$Author}:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210412-221659-758980#%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas:)
